<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=10158916967535></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f10158916967535><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=item.html?item=10201&mid=10158916967535>RE: Hmm...</a> <a id=fs8 href=item.html?item=10201&mid=10158916967535#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=85751><span id= >Joim</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>1 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Mar 11th 7:10 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Sure, warriors can get big crips, but what about paladins with Slay Undead 3?<br>Level 3 Slay Undead allows paladins to get slay hits for over 100 times the base damage of the weapon, allowing a melee hit for almost 8000 with this amazing hammer.<br><br>But yes, this would be the ultimate weapon for an auto-riposte discing warrior/monk; significantly better than a weighted axe:<br>Modal damage for weighted axe at 60 is 110 (from damage bonus) + 2x45 (base damage) = 200<br>Modal damage for Drathor Great Hammer at 60 is 84 (supposing the damage bonus at 60 for 95 delay is 73 as in the screenshot) + 2x74 (base damage) = 232<br>So the modal damage on the hammer is better on ripostes (delay independent), and better per time on auto-attack because of the higher modal damage and also lower delay. (disclaimer: modal damage per delay isn't the only important thing to look at when comparing weapons)<br><br>All in all, I'd love a pair of these hammers - one for both my monk and paladin.<br>- Joim<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Mon Mar 11 19:22:59 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
